        "BC2 tag",
        "beta-catenin epitope"
      ]
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_affinity_matrix",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "pending",
      "cat:claimType": "affinity_matrix",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"elution\": \"competitive elution with free BC2 peptide (PDRKAAVSHWQQ), 0.1\\u20131 mM\", \"matrix\": \"BC2-Nb covalently coupled to a solid support\", \"recovery\": \"~60% at 0.1 mM, ~80% at 1 mM peptide; eluted protein retains native fold\", \"robustness\": \"binding tolerant to 2% SDS, 4 M urea, up to 1.5 M GdmCl, various detergents and salt\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "high",
      "cat:crossChecked": false,
      "cat:sourceQuote": "competitive elution was highly efficient as ~60% and ~80% of GFP were detected in elution fractions after addition of 0.1 mM and 1 mM BC2 peptide, respectively ... the BC2 peptide can efficiently displace BC2-bound proteins in their natively folded state",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Results",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:26791954"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:26791954"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_affinity_matrix_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "BC2-tagged proteins can be purified in one step on a BC2-Nb affinity matrix and gently eluted in natively folded form by competition with free BC2 peptide (~60\u201380% recovery at 0.1\u20131 mM); capture also tolerates harsh conditions (2% SDS, 4 M urea, 1.5 M GdmCl)."
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_affinity_matrix_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_application",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "pending",
      "cat:claimType": "application",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"advantage\": \"minimal epitope and small binder reduce steric hindrance and linkage error\", \"applications\": [\"direct Western blot detection\", \"immunofluorescence / immunocytochemistry\"], \"reagent\": \"BC2-Nb conjugated to an organic dye\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "high",
      "cat:crossChecked": false,
      "cat:sourceQuote": "the fluorescently modified BC2-Nb directly detects BC2-tagged proteins in Western blots without the need of a secondary antibody ... the fluorescently labeled BC2-Nb specifically binds to ectopically expressed BC2T fusion proteins and can therefore be applied for direct antigen detection in immunocytochemistry.",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Results",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:26791954"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:26791954"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_application_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "Fluorescently labeled BC2-Nb detects BC2-tagged proteins directly in Western blot (no secondary antibody) and visualizes BC2-tagged subcellular structures by immunofluorescence."
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_application_dstorm",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "pending",
      "cat:claimType": "application",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"application\": \"dSTORM super-resolution microscopy\", \"feature\": \"minimal linkage error; demonstrated on endogenous CRISPR-tagged proteins\", \"hosts\": [\"mammalian cells\", \"yeast (S. pombe)\"], \"reagent\": \"bivalent BC2-Nb (bivBC2-Nb)\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "medium",
      "cat:crossChecked": false,
      "cat:sourceQuote": "a short peptide tag-specific nanobody (BC2-tag/bivBC2-Nb) ... bivBC2-Nb staining results in a close-grained fluorophore labeling with minimal linkage errors. This allowed us to perform high-quality dSTORM imaging of various targets in mammalian and yeast cells.",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Abstract",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:29500346"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:29500346"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_application_dstorm_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "A bivalent BC2-Nb (bivBC2-Nb) enables dense, low-linkage-error fluorophore labeling of BC2-tagged targets for dSTORM super-resolution imaging in mammalian and yeast cells, including endogenous, CRISPR-tagged loci."
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_application_dstorm_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_application_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_binding_affinity",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "pending",
      "cat:claimType": "binding_affinity",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"Kd\": \"~1.4 nM\", \"binder\": \"BC2-Nb\", \"binder_type\": \"nanobody\", \"measurement_method\": \"surface plasmon resonance\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "high",
      "cat:crossChecked": false,
      "cat:sourceQuote": "We have shown that the BC2-Nb binds BC2-epitope-tagged proteins with a K of ~1.4 nM",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Discussion",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:26791954"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:26791954"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_binding_affinity_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "The BC2 tag (PDRKAAVSHWQQ) is bound by the BC2 nanobody (BC2-Nb) with a dissociation constant of ~1.4 nM, measured by surface plasmon resonance."
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_binding_affinity_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_mechanism",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "pending",
      "cat:claimType": "mechanism",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"affinity_source\": \"backbone hydrogen bonds (sequence-independent)\", \"binding_mode\": \"headlock \\u2014 peptide forms a beta-strand integrated into the nanobody beta-sheet\", \"clamp\": \"Arg106 (CDR3)\\u2013Glu44 (FR2) salt bridge over the bound peptide\", \"structures\": \"crystal structures of BC2-Nb (2.0 A) and BC2-Nb/BC2T complex (1.0 A)\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "high",
      "cat:crossChecked": false,
      "cat:sourceQuote": "the BC2 peptide adopts a \u03b2-strand conformation that is part of a \u03b2-sheet structure formed by the CDR3 and the framework regions. Numerous backbone hydrogen bonds provide affinity, and a salt bridge between Arg106 of CDR3 and Glu44 of FR2 embraces the bound peptide in a headlock-like fashion.",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Discussion",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:26791954"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:26791954"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_mechanism_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "BC2-Nb binds BC2T in an extended beta-strand conformation that becomes part of a beta-sheet in the nanobody ('headlock' binding): affinity comes from many backbone hydrogen bonds, while a salt bridge (Nb Arg106\u2013Glu44) clamps the bound peptide in place."
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_mechanism_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_origin",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "pending",
      "cat:claimType": "origin",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"residues\": \"16\\u201327\", \"sequence\": \"PDRKAAVSHWQQ\", \"source_protein\": \"human beta-catenin (CTNB1)\", \"uniprot\": \"P35222\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "high",
      "cat:crossChecked": false,
      "cat:sourceQuote": "BC2-Nb, recognizes a short linear epitope corresponding to residues 16\u201327 of \u03b2-catenin ... the peptide epitope, hereafter referred to as BC2 tag (BC2T)",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Introduction",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:26791954"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:26791954"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_origin_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "BC2T is a natural linear epitope corresponding to residues 16\u201327 of human beta-catenin (UniProt P35222), repurposed as a minimal affinity/detection tag."
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_origin_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_placement",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "pending",
      "cat:claimType": "placement",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"caveat\": \"N-terminal tag can be partially proteolyzed on cell lysis\", \"position_dependence\": \"none for recognition; both work\", \"positions_tested\": [\"N-terminal\", \"C-terminal\"]}",
      "cat:confidence": "high",
      "cat:crossChecked": false,
      "cat:sourceQuote": "the N- or the C-terminally localized BC2 tag is equally well recognized by the BC2 nanotrap. For N-terminally BC2-tagged GFP we observed an additional band in the non-bound fraction. This indicates that the BC2 tag might be proteolytically removed upon cellular lysis",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Discussion",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:26791954"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:26791954"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_placement_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "The BC2 tag is recognized equally well at the N- or C-terminus of a fusion protein; N-terminal placement can be susceptible to partial proteolytic removal during lysis."
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_placement_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_post_translational",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "pending",
      "cat:claimType": "post_translational",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"consequence\": \"reduced BC2-Nb binding; preference for non-phosphorylated peptide\", \"modification\": \"phosphorylation of Ser23 (S8 of BC2T)\", \"relevance\": \"matters mainly when tagging endogenous beta-catenin; the S8 hydroxyl is one of the four specificity-determining contacts\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "medium",
      "cat:crossChecked": false,
      "cat:sourceQuote": "the chromobody signal allowed us to trace the accumulation of diffusible, hypo-phosphorylated \u03b2-catenin",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Abstract",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:25595278"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:25595278"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_post_translational_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "Because BC2T derives from beta-catenin, phosphorylation of Ser23 (position 8 of the tag, S8) by the canonical destruction complex disfavors BC2-Nb binding; the nanobody preferentially recognizes the non-/hypo-phosphorylated form."
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_post_translational_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_sequence_feature",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "pending",
      "cat:claimType": "sequence_feature",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"method\": \"positional scanning peptide library immunoprecipitation + LC-MS\", \"most_critical_residue\": \"W10\", \"specificity_determining_residues\": [\"R3\", \"A6\", \"S8\", \"W10\"], \"tolerant_positions\": [1, 2, 4, 5, 7, 9, 11, 12]}",
      "cat:confidence": "high",
      "cat:crossChecked": false,
      "cat:sourceQuote": "BC2T residues at positions 1, 2, 4, 5, 7, 9, 11, and 12 can be replaced without affecting the epitope binding properties ... The tryptophan at position 10 appears to be an invariable specificity-determining amino acid",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Results",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:26791954"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:26791954"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_sequence_feature_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "Specificity for BC2-Nb is determined by only four BC2T side chains \u2014 R3, A6, S8 and W10 (W10 invariable and most critical); the other eight positions can be substituted without loss of binding, making the tag re-engineerable."
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_sequence_feature_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_sequence_variant",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "pending",
      "cat:claimType": "sequence_variant",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"catalog_part\": \"Spot_tag\", \"shared_binder\": \"BC2 nanobody lineage\", \"substitutions_vs_BC2T\": [\"K4V\", \"A5R\", \"Q11S\", \"Q12S\"], \"variant_name\": \"Spot-tag\", \"variant_sequence\": \"PDRVRAVSHWSS\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "medium",
      "cat:crossChecked": false,
      "cat:sourceQuote": "a short peptide tag-specific nanobody (BC2-tag/bivBC2-Nb)",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Abstract",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:29500346"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:29500346"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_sequence_variant_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "An engineered, re-surfaced variant of BC2T named Spot-tag (PDRVRAVSHWSS; four substitutions K4V, A5R, Q11S, Q12S) is recognized by the same BC2-Nb lineage and is optimized for dSTORM labeling; it is held as a separate catalog part (Spot_tag)."
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_sequence_variant_44d",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "pending",
      "cat:claimType": "sequence_variant",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"Kd_44D\": \"~1.4e-7 M (vs ~1.4e-9 M wild type)\", \"engineered_element\": \"BC2-Nb (binder), variant 44D\", \"note\": \"the tag sequence is unchanged; this variant is on the binder side\", \"outcome\": \"mild elution (pH 3.5 or neutral arginine/propylene-glycol buffer), ~94\\u201395% recovery, >90% purity in one step\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "medium",
      "cat:crossChecked": false,
      "cat:sourceQuote": "The site-directed mutation led to the equilibrium dissociation constant (K) of BC2-Nb changing from 1.4 \u00d7 10M to 1.4 \u00d7 10M (44D) ... Protein recovery reached 94% at pH 3.5 for 44D-based resin",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Abstract",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:35780707"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:35780707"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:BC2_tag_claim_sequence_variant_44d_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "Engineering the BC2 nanobody (not the tag) \u2014 e.g. the 44D variant \u2014 lowers affinity for BC2T ~100-fold (Kd ~1.4\u00d710\u207b\u2077 M), allowing one-step immunoaffinity purification of BC2T-tagged proteins with product recovery up to ~94\u201395% under mild elution."
    },
