        "@id": "part:HaloTag_claim_labeling_kinetics_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "HaloTag7 labels its chloroalkane substrates rapidly; the apparent second-order rate constant spans more than six orders of magnitude depending on the attached fluorophore, with rhodamine-chloroalkane substrates reacting near the diffusion limit and HaloTag7 labeling more than 100-fold faster than SNAP-tag for matched substrates."
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:HaloTag_claim_labeling_kinetics_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:HaloTag_claim_mechanism",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "pending",
      "cat:claimType": "mechanism",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"bond\": \"covalent ester\", \"ligand\": \"synthetic chloroalkane linker\", \"reversibility\": \"essentially irreversible\", \"scaffold\": \"haloalkane dehalogenase (DhaA, Rhodococcus rhodochrous)\", \"tag_class\": \"self-labeling protein tag\", \"trapping_mutation\": \"base catalytic His -> Phe\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "high",
      "cat:crossChecked": false,
      "cat:sourceQuote": "The protein tag (HaloTag) is a modified haloalkane dehalogenase designed to covalently bind to synthetic ligands... Covalent bond formation between the protein tag and the chloroalkane linker is highly specific, occurs rapidly under physiological conditions, and is essentially irreversible.",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Abstract",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:18533659"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:18533659"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:HaloTag_claim_mechanism_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "HaloTag is an engineered haloalkane dehalogenase that forms a covalent, essentially irreversible ester bond with a synthetic chloroalkane ligand. The nucleophilic aspartate at the alpha/beta-hydrolase nucleophile elbow attacks the terminal carbon of the chloroalkane, displacing chloride; an engineered His->Phe substitution at the base catalytic histidine prevents the normal second hydrolytic step, trapping the covalent enzyme-ligand intermediate."
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:HaloTag_claim_mechanism_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:HaloTag_claim_sequence_variant",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "pending",
      "cat:claimType": "sequence_variant",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"length_aa\": 297, \"mutations_vs_parent\": 21, \"parent\": \"DhaA haloalkane dehalogenase (Rhodococcus rhodochrous)\", \"variant_name\": \"HaloTag7\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "high",
      "cat:crossChecked": false,
      "cat:sourceQuote": "we have developed a novel protein tag, HaloTag7, engineered to enhance expression and solubility of recombinant proteins and to provide efficient protein purification coupled with tag removal.",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Abstract",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:19464373"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:19464373"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:HaloTag_claim_sequence_variant_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "This 297-aa sequence is HaloTag7, an engineered variant of Rhodococcus DhaA carrying 21 amino-acid substitutions relative to the parent dehalogenase that enhance soluble expression, folding, and ligand-binding kinetics; it is the workhorse HaloTag scaffold for downstream applications."
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:HaloTag_claim_sequence_variant_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:HaloTag_claim_solubility_enhancement",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "pending",
      "cat:claimType": "strength_class",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"host\": \"Escherichia coli\", \"n_proteins\": 23, \"property\": \"solubility enhancement\", \"soluble_fraction_GST\": \"39%\", \"soluble_fraction_HaloTag7\": \"74%\", \"soluble_fraction_His6\": \"22%\", \"soluble_fraction_MBP\": \"52%\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "high",
      "cat:crossChecked": false,
      "cat:sourceQuote": "74% of the proteins were produced in soluble form when fused to HaloTag7 compared to 52%, 39% and 22%, respectively, for the other tags.",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Abstract",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:19464373"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:19464373"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:HaloTag_claim_solubility_enhancement_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "As an N-terminal fusion partner in E. coli, HaloTag7 enhanced soluble expression: 74% of 23 test human proteins were produced in soluble form when fused to HaloTag7, versus 52% for MBP, 39% for GST, and 22% for a His6 tag."
    },
