    {
      "@id": "part:LPETG_tag_claim_application",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "sources-pending",
      "cat:claimType": "application",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"acceptor\": \"N-terminal (oligo)glycine on the partner (peptide, protein, small molecule, surface, D-peptide, or branched peptide)\", \"founding_in_vitro_demonstration\": \"use of LPETG for in vitro protein engineering / conjugation to (D)-peptides, branched peptides, and small molecules bearing an N-terminal glycine\", \"handle\": \"C-terminal LPETG on the protein of interest\", \"method\": \"sortase-mediated protein ligation (sortagging)\", \"uses\": [\"site-specific bioconjugation / labeling\", \"protein-protein and protein-peptide ligation\", \"protein immobilization\", \"C-terminal and internal-loop labeling of proteins\"]}",
      "cat:confidence": "medium",
      "cat:crossChecked": false,
      "cat:lastChecked": {
        "@type": "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date",
        "@value": "2026-06-22"
      },
      "cat:sourceQuote": "Sortase-mediated protein ligation: a new method for protein engineering",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "title and abstract",
      "cat:usefulness": "high",
      "cat:usefulnessRationale": "Specifies the operational method (sortase-mediated ligation), the binding partners (C-terminal LPETG + N-terminal Gly), and concrete applications (bioconjugation, immobilization, labeling); enables direct selection and use of this part over alternatives",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:14995162"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:14995162"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:LPETG_tag_claim_application_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "LPETG is the standard C-terminal handle for sortase-mediated protein ligation (sortagging): a protein carrying C-terminal LPETG can be site-specifically conjugated to molecules bearing an N-terminal glycine"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:LPETG_tag_claim_application_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:LPETG_tag_claim_host_range",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "verified",
      "cat:claimType": "host_range",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"element_type\": \"sortase recognition / cell-wall sorting signal (peptide motif)\", \"enzyme_origin\": \"Staphylococcus aureus sortase A (SrtA); commonly the evolved pentamutant eSrtA for enhanced activity\", \"host_dependence\": \"none for the motif itself; ligation requires sortase A supplied in vitro (or co-expressed in vivo)\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "high",
      "cat:crossChecked": true,
      "cat:lastChecked": {
        "@type": "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date",
        "@value": "2026-06-22"
      },
      "cat:sourceQuote": "Sortase (SrtA), a transpeptidase from Staphylococcus aureus, catalyzes a cell-wall sorting reaction at an LPXTG motif by cleaving between threonine and glycine and subsequently joining the carboxyl group of threonine to an amino group of pentaglycine. We have applied this transpeptidyl activity of sortase to in vitro protein ligation. We found that in the presence of sortase, protein/peptide with an LPXTG motif can be specifically ligated to an aminoglycine protein/peptide via an amide bond. Additionally, sortase can even conjugate substrates such as (d)-peptides, synthetic branched peptides, and aminoglycine-derivatized small molecules to the C terminus of a recombinant protein.",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "title and abstract",
      "cat:usefulness": "high",
      "cat:usefulnessRationale": "Datasheet_slot claim: directly influences designer choice of expression system; explains why any organism/context works (motif is sequence + separate enzyme)",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:14995162"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:14995162"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:LPETG_tag_claim_host_range_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "Host-agnostic sequence element: LPETG is a short peptide motif and the sortase enzyme is supplied separately, so the handle functions independently of the expression host"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:LPETG_tag_claim_host_range_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:LPETG_tag_claim_mechanism",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "verified",
      "cat:claimType": "mechanism",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"enzyme_class\": \"transpeptidase (cysteine acyltransferase)\", \"natural_function\": \"anchoring surface proteins to the Gram-positive cell-wall peptidoglycan (via the lipid II / pentaglycine cross-bridge as natural acceptor)\", \"net_result\": \"site-specific ligation of an LPXTG-tagged protein to a Gly-n-bearing partner, reconstituting an LPETGG... junction\", \"step_1\": \"cleavage of the Thr-Gly bond of LPXTG and formation of a covalent acyl-enzyme thioester intermediate at the active-site cysteine\", \"step_2\": \"resolution of the thioester by nucleophilic attack of an N-terminal oligoglycine (Gly-n) amine, ligating the LPET-acyl group to the acceptor\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "high",
      "cat:crossChecked": true,
      "cat:lastChecked": {
        "@type": "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date",
        "@value": "2026-06-22"
      },
      "cat:sourceQuote": "Protein A is cleaved by a transpeptidase, sortase, between the threonine and the glycine of a conserved LPXTG motif (5). The carboxyl group of threonine is amide-linked to the amino group of the pentaglycine cross-bridge, thereby tethering the COOH-terminal end of protein A to the bacterial cell wall (6). [Lines 211-217]. The srtA gene specifies a protein of 206 amino acids with a potential NH2-terminal signal peptide/membrane anchor sequence and a presumed active-site cysteine at position 184, consistent with the observation that the cell wall sorting reaction is sensitive to reagents that modify sulfhydryl groups. [Lines 418-424]. Together, our data reveal that srtA encodes sortase, the transpeptidase that anchors surface proteins to the bacterial cell wall (24). [Lines 450-452]",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "title and abstract",
      "cat:usefulness": "high",
      "cat:usefulnessRationale": "Explains the molecular mechanism of sortase-mediated ligation, critical for understanding how LPETG functions operationally and how it differs from passive affinity/detection tags; directly guides use (cysteine-dependent, requires oligoglycine acceptor, results in covalent ligation)",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:10427003"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:10427003"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:LPETG_tag_claim_mechanism_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "Sortase A is a transpeptidase: it cleaves LPXTG to form an acyl-enzyme thioester at the active-site Cys, then transfers the acyl group to an N-terminal oligoglycine acceptor (transpeptidation)"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:LPETG_tag_claim_mechanism_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:LPETG_tag_claim_natural_origin",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "flagged",
      "cat:claimType": "origin",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"also_present_in\": \"FnbA (UniProt P14738) at positions 982-986, and many other Gram-positive surface proteins as the conserved LPXTG class signal\", \"biological_context\": \"C-terminal cell-wall sorting signal directing SrtA-mediated covalent anchoring to peptidoglycan\", \"origin_protein\": \"Immunoglobulin G-binding protein A (Protein A / SpA), Staphylococcus aureus (UniProt P02976)\", \"residues\": \"482-486 (LPETG), annotated Motif 'LPXTG sorting signal'\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "low",
      "cat:crossChecked": false,
      "cat:lastChecked": {
        "@type": "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date",
        "@value": "2026-06-22"
      },
      "cat:sourceQuote": "Protein A is released into the Staphylococcus aureus culture supernatant with an unprocessed sorting signal",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "title and abstract",
      "cat:usefulness": "low",
      "cat:usefulnessRationale": "Tautological \u2014 restates that the part IS the native LPXTG sorting signal from S. aureus Protein A, a fact already evident from the part's name and description; provides no actionable design information, comparative discrimination, or failure-mode knowledge that an engineer would consult when choosing or operating this part.",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:25644005"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:25644005"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:LPETG_tag_claim_natural_origin_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:comment": "superseded by natural_origin__v2: The asserted residue positions (482-486) are factually incorrect per the primary source, which states the sorting signal spans residues 474-508 with the LPETG motif at positions 470-474. The origin claim itself (that LPETG is native to SpA) is supported, but the positional coordinates must be corrected.",
      "rdfs:label": "LPETG is the native LPXTG sorting signal of S. aureus Protein A (SpA); native SpA carries the exact LPETG sequence in its precursor"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:LPETG_tag_claim_natural_origin__v2",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "verified",
      "cat:claimType": "origin",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"also_present_in\": \"FnbA (UniProt P14738) at positions 982-986, and many other Gram-positive surface proteins as the conserved LPXTG class signal\", \"biological_context\": \"C-terminal cell-wall sorting signal directing SrtA-mediated covalent anchoring to peptidoglycan\", \"origin_protein\": \"Immunoglobulin G-binding protein A (Protein A / SpA), Staphylococcus aureus (UniProt P02976)\", \"residues\": \"470-474 (LPETG), or more broadly 474-508 for the complete sorting signal\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "low",
      "cat:crossChecked": true,
