    {
      "@id": "part:LPETG_tag_claim_placement",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "verified",
      "cat:claimType": "placement",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"junction_after_ligation\": \"LPETGG... (the acceptor's N-terminal Gly residues become part of the product)\", \"position\": \"C-terminal of the protein of interest (commonly POI-LPETG-His6 so an affinity tag downstream is removed upon ligation)\", \"structural_requirement\": \"the LPXTG motif should lie in a flexible, solvent-accessible / unstructured region for efficient cleavage\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "high",
      "cat:crossChecked": true,
      "cat:lastChecked": {
        "@type": "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date",
        "@value": "2026-06-22"
      },
      "cat:sourceQuote": "The sortase-recognition sequence is usually engineered at the C terminus of the protein to be modified, with the G or A residue in amide linkage, followed by an affinity purification handle (e.g., His6) that is lost upon reaction. The efficiency of the sortase-mediated reaction depends on the flexibility and accessibility of the region comprising the sortase A-recognition motif. As long as the LPXTG/A motif is introduced in an unstructured segment of the substrate protein, sortase can recognize the sequence. An LPXTG motif that is highly structured is usually a poor sortase substrate.",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "title and abstract",
      "cat:usefulness": "high",
      "cat:usefulnessRationale": "Actionable constraints on C-terminal placement, accessibility requirements, linker design strategy, and junction composition are essential design parameters for successful sortagging applications",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:23989673"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:23989673"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:LPETG_tag_claim_placement_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "LPETG must be placed at (or near) the C-terminus of the protein of interest and in an accessible, unstructured region; the Gly that follows it is consumed/relocated by the ligation"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:LPETG_tag_claim_placement_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:LPETG_tag_claim_recognition_specificity",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "verified",
      "cat:claimType": "recognition_specificity",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"consensus\": \"Leu-Pro-any-Thr-Gly\", \"enzyme\": \"Sortase A (SrtA), a transpeptidase/cysteine acyltransferase\", \"positions\": \"P5-P4-P3-P2-P1-P1' (Leu-Pro-Glu-Thr | Gly)\", \"recognition_motif\": \"LPXTG (here LPETG, X=Glu)\", \"scissile_bond\": \"between P1 Thr and P1' Gly (LPET|G)\", \"x_position_note\": \"Glu (E) is commonly found at the X position of efficient natural and engineering SrtA substrates\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "high",
      "cat:crossChecked": true,
      "cat:lastChecked": {
        "@type": "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date",
        "@value": "2026-06-22"
      },
      "cat:sourceQuote": "Cleavage between the threonine and the glycine of the LPXTG motif liberates the carboxyl of threonine to form an amide bond with the amino group of the pentaglycine crossbridge (2, 3), thereby tethering the C terminus end of surface proteins to the bacterial peptidoglycan (4\u20137). [Lines 25-28]. Additionally: Staphylococcal extracts, as well as purified sortase, catalyze the hydroxylaminolysis of peptides bearing an LPXTG motif [lines 14-15]. And: Purified SrtADN was incubated with the LPXTG peptide Dabcyl-QALPETGEE-Edans, and cleavage was monitored [lines 179-188], demonstrating LPETG as an active substrate for SrtA-mediated cleavage.",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "title and abstract",
      "cat:usefulness": "high",
      "cat:usefulnessRationale": "Directly actionable for designers: specifies exact enzyme (SrtA), recognition sequence (LPETG), and scissile bond position (Thr|Gly). This information discriminates LPETG from other tags and determines whether a protein construct will be efficiently processed.",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:10535938"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:10535938"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:LPETG_tag_claim_recognition_specificity_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "LPETG is an instance of the LPXTG sortase recognition motif; sortase A cleaves between the Thr and the Gly (LPET|G)"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:LPETG_tag_claim_recognition_specificity_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:LPETG_tag_claim_sequence_variant",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "flagged",
      "cat:claimType": "sequence_variant",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"evolved_catalyst\": \"eSrtA pentamutant (P94R/D160N/D165A/K190E/K196T), reported with markedly improved activity toward LPETG\", \"motif_variants\": \"LPXTG class; X is most often Glu in efficient substrates (LPETG); other X residues occur in natural signals\", \"orthogonal_motifs\": \"engineered sortases reprogrammed to recognize LAXTG and LPXSG, independent of canonical LPETG, enabling dual labeling\", \"reported_improvement\": \"~140-fold increased activity vs wild-type SrtA (quantitative value from a primary text not directly accessed)\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "low",
      "cat:crossChecked": false,
      "cat:lastChecked": {
        "@type": "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date",
        "@value": "2026-06-22"
      },
      "cat:sourceQuote": "A general strategy for the evolution of bond-forming enzymes using yeast display",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "title and abstract",
      "cat:usefulness": "high",
      "cat:usefulnessRationale": "Discriminates LPETG from engineered variants, provides quantitative enzyme performance data (fold activity improvement), and specifies which evolved sortase (pentamutant) to use \u2014 directly operational for a designer choosing between WT and evolved SrtA.",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:21697512"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:21697512"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:LPETG_tag_claim_sequence_variant_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:comment": "The \"orthogonal_motifs\" clause (LAXTG/LPXSG recognition by engineered sortases) is not discussed in the cited paper (Chen et al. 2011); it appears to conflate two separate publications. The pentamutant's actual 120-fold activity (not 140-fold) is documented in Table 1 line 791 of Chen et al.",
      "rdfs:label": "The catalyst, not the motif, is the main engineered variant: the evolved SrtA pentamutant (eSrtA) has greatly improved activity toward LPETG; orthogonal sortases instead recognize altered motifs (LAXTG / LPXSG) rather than LPETG"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:LPETG_tag_claim_sequence_variant_provenance",
