    {
      "@id": "part:SnoopTag_claim_application",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "verified",
      "cat:claimType": "application",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"applications\": [\"covalent fusion of two protein modules\", \"sequential / programmable polyprotein ('polyproteam') assembly when combined orthogonally with SpyTag/SpyCatcher\", \"plug-and-display on multivalent scaffolds\"]}",
      "cat:confidence": "high",
      "cat:crossChecked": true,
      "cat:lastChecked": {
        "@type": "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date",
        "@value": "2026-06-22"
      },
      "cat:sourceQuote": "Solid-phase attachment followed by sequential SpyTag or SnoopTag reaction between building-blocks enabled iterative extension. Linear, branched, and combinatorial polyproteins were synthesized",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Abstract",
      "cat:usefulness": "high",
      "cat:usefulnessRationale": "Concrete, selection-relevant applications (irreversible covalent assembly, programmable polyproteams, modular display) with operationally actionable details (solid-phase attachment, sequential iterative reactions, orthogonality with SpyTag/SpyCatcher). Directly addresses how an engineer would use SnoopTag.",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:26787909"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:26787909"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:SnoopTag_claim_application_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "Programmable, irreversible protein-protein conjugation and modular assembly"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:SnoopTag_claim_application_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:SnoopTag_claim_mechanism",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "verified",
      "cat:claimType": "mechanism",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"bond_type\": \"isopeptide\", \"mechanism\": \"Reactive peptide split from the RrgA D4 domain; on mixing with the partner protein SnoopCatcher it reconstitutes the split domain and forms a spontaneous intramolecular-derived intermolecular isopeptide (amide) bond between a Lys side chain on SnoopTag and an Asn side chain on SnoopCatcher, covalently and irreversibly locking the two units together.\", \"partner\": \"SnoopCatcher\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "high",
      "cat:crossChecked": true,
      "cat:lastChecked": {
        "@type": "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date",
        "@value": "2026-06-22"
      },
      "cat:sourceQuote": "By engineering the adhesin RrgA from Streptococcus pneumoniae, we developed the peptide SnoopTag, which formed a spontaneous isopeptide bond to its protein partner SnoopCatcher with >99% yield and no cross-reaction to SpyTag/SpyCatcher. A spontaneous isopeptide bond forms in the D4 Ig-like domain of RrgA between residues Lys742 and Asn854. We split the D4 domain in the loop following the N-terminal \u03b2-strand and, after exploring various extensions and truncations of the two partners, settled on the peptide tag we termed SnoopTag (residues 734\u2013745) and the protein partner we named SnoopCatcher (residues 749\u2013860). Mutations in the putative reactive Lys742 of SnoopTag (SnoopTag KA-MBP) and the putative reactive Asn854 of SnoopCatcher (SnoopCatcher NA) abolished reaction.",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Abstract",
      "cat:usefulness": "high",
      "cat:usefulnessRationale": "Describes the core functional mechanism (isopeptide bond between Lys and Asn) and partner (SnoopCatcher), directly actionable for designers choosing and deploying this part; specifies reaction chemistry and irreversibility, differentiates from SpyTag.",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:26787909"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:26787909"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:SnoopTag_claim_mechanism_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "Spontaneous covalent isopeptide-bond formation with SnoopCatcher"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:SnoopTag_claim_mechanism_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:SnoopTag_claim_origin",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "flagged",
      "cat:claimType": "origin",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"derivation\": \"split-domain engineering of the RrgA isopeptide-bond-forming domain into a peptide (SnoopTag) and protein (SnoopCatcher) pair\", \"organism\": \"Streptococcus pneumoniae\", \"parent_protein\": \"RrgA pilus adhesin (UniProt A7KT94)\", \"parent_region\": \"D4 (CnaA-like) domain, residues 727\\u2013738\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "medium",
      "cat:crossChecked": false,
      "cat:lastChecked": {
        "@type": "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date",
        "@value": "2026-06-22"
      },
      "cat:sourceQuote": "By engineering the adhesin RrgA from [Streptococcus pneumoniae], we developed the peptide SnoopTag",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Abstract",
      "cat:usefulness": "medium",
      "cat:usefulnessRationale": "Discriminates the part's source organism and parent protein structure (explains isopeptide-bond mechanism origin), but specific residue coordinates have low operational utility since designers use the final 12-aa sequence, not parent coordinates.",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:26787909"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:26787909"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:SnoopTag_claim_origin_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:comment": "The paper clearly specifies that after optimization, SnoopTag comprises residues 734-745 of RrgA D4, not 727-738; this is a straightforward factual correction from the Methods section.",
      "rdfs:label": "Derived from the RrgA pilus adhesin D4 domain of S. pneumoniae"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:SnoopTag_claim_origin_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:SnoopTag_claim_orthogonality",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "verified",
      "cat:claimType": "caveat",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"cross_reaction\": \"none\", \"orthogonal_to\": [\"SpyTag\", \"SpyCatcher\"]}",
      "cat:confidence": "high",
      "cat:crossChecked": true,
      "cat:lastChecked": {
        "@type": "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date",
        "@value": "2026-06-22"
      },
      "cat:sourceQuote": "SnoopTag/SnoopCatcher reacted with each other but not with an alternative peptide/protein pair, SpyTag/SpyCatcher. ... Each partner reacted efficiently with its cognate pair, but we found no trace of cross-reaction, even after overnight incubation (Fig. 2C).",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Abstract (Significance)",
      "cat:usefulness": "high",
      "cat:usefulnessRationale": "Directly discriminates SnoopTag from SpyTag in design choice; engineers MUST know about orthogonality when selecting which tag system to use for polyprotein assembly where multiple tags are required.",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:26787909"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:26787909"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:SnoopTag_claim_orthogonality_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "Orthogonal to SpyTag/SpyCatcher (no cross-reaction)"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:SnoopTag_claim_orthogonality_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
