    {
      "@id": "part:birA_claim_application",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "verified",
      "cat:claimType": "application",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"cognate_substrate\": \"AviTag / biotin acceptor peptide (BAP); 15-aa GLNDIFEAQKIEWHE derived from the 13-residue consensus\", \"downstream\": \"avidin/streptavidin affinity capture, detection, immobilization\", \"use\": \"site-specific in vivo or in vitro mono-biotinylation of an acceptor-peptide-tagged protein\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "high",
      "cat:crossChecked": true,
      "cat:lastChecked": {
        "@type": "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date",
        "@value": "2026-06-22"
      },
      "cat:sourceQuote": "Cell surface proteins tagged with a 15-amino acid peptide are biotinylated by Escherichia coli biotin ligase (BirA), whereas endogenous proteins are not modified. The biotin group then allows sensitive and stable binding by streptavidin conjugates. This protocol describes the optimal use of BirA and streptavidin for site-specific labeling.",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:usefulness": "high",
      "cat:usefulnessRationale": "Specifies the paired use (BirA + AviTag), exact substrate sequence, operational details (in vivo/in vitro), and downstream applications (capture, detection, immobilization)\u2014directly actionable for part selection and use in biotechnology workflows.",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:18323822"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:18323822"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:birA_claim_application_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "BirA is the enzyme of the AviTag/BAP site-specific biotinylation system: co-expressed with (or applied to) a fused acceptor peptide, it biotinylates a single lysine, enabling avidin/streptavidin capture, detection, and immobilization."
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:birA_claim_application_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "secondary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:birA_claim_host_range",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "flagged",
      "cat:claimType": "host_range",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"basis\": \"background biotinylation is minimal in eukaryotes because biotin is a rare modification\", \"native_host\": \"Escherichia coli\", \"validated_hosts\": [\"mammalian cells\", \"yeast\", \"flies (Drosophila)\", \"worms (C. elegans)\", \"bacteria\"]}",
      "cat:confidence": "medium",
      "cat:crossChecked": false,
      "cat:lastChecked": {
        "@type": "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date",
        "@value": "2026-06-22"
      },
      "cat:sourceQuote": "Because biotinylation is a rare modification, in mammalian cells it is restricted primarily to only a few carboxylases; BAT-independent binding is minimal.",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Results",
      "cat:usefulness": "high",
      "cat:usefulnessRationale": "Directly addresses a critical selection parameter for BioID/BirA deployment: explains the mechanistic basis for low background biotinylation in eukaryotes (rare natural modification, restricted to carboxylases), which is operationally actionable for anyone choosing this system for proximity labeling in non-E. coli hosts.",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:22412018"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:22412018"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:birA_claim_host_range_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:comment": "The asserted host list (yeast, Drosophila, C. elegans, bacteria) is NOT validated in this paper\u2014only mammalian cells (HEK293, HeLa) are experimentally tested. The discussion section speculates BioID should work in \"essentially any accessible cell type, mammalian or otherwise\" but provides no experimental evidence for non-mammalian hosts; this is theoretical extrapolation, not empirical validation.",
      "rdfs:label": "BirA biotinylation is highly specific in eukaryotic cells because endogenous biotinylation is restricted to a few carboxylases; this makes the BirA + acceptor-peptide system functional across mammalian and other heterologous hosts."
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:birA_claim_host_range_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:birA_claim_mechanism",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "flagged",
      "cat:claimType": "mechanism",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"dual_function\": \"biotin-protein ligase AND bio-5'-AMP-dependent transcriptional repressor of the biotin biosynthesis operon\", \"reaction\": \"biotin + ATP -> biotinoyl-5'-AMP (intermediate held in active site) -> biotin transferred to acceptor lysine\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "medium",
      "cat:crossChecked": false,
      "cat:lastChecked": {
        "@type": "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date",
        "@value": "2026-06-22"
      },
      "cat:sourceQuote": "Biotinylation by BirA is a two-step process. The first of these combines biotin and ATP to form biotinoyl-5'-AMP (bioAMP). This activated biotin is held within the BirA active site until it reacts with a specific lysine residue of the BAT sequence in the second step.",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Introduction",
      "cat:usefulness": "high",
      "cat:usefulnessRationale": "Describes the core catalytic mechanism of BirA, which is essential for understanding how the part functions in biotinylation applications (AviTag, BioID, TurboID) \u2014 directly operationally relevant to anyone designing with this enzyme.",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:22412018"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:22412018"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:birA_claim_mechanism_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:comment": "The two-step reaction and biotinoyl-5'-AMP intermediate formation are fully supported. However, the claim's second component \u2014 that bio-5'-AMP is the corepressor of the biotin operon \u2014 is NOT addressed in the Roux 2012 paper. The paper notes BirA's repressor function but does not discuss the mechanistic role of bio-5'-AMP in repression. This claim likely draws on earlier primary literature (Barker & Campbell, or others cited in the part's references), not from Roux 2012.",
      "rdfs:label": "BirA catalyses biotinylation in two steps: it condenses biotin with ATP to form biotinoyl-5'-AMP, then transfers biotin to a specific lysine of the acceptor substrate; bio-5'-AMP is also the corepressor of the biotin operon."
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:birA_claim_mechanism_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:birA_claim_regulation",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "verified",
      "cat:claimType": "regulation",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"corepressor\": \"biotinoyl-5'-AMP (bio-5'-AMP), which drives dimerization required for DNA binding\", \"operator\": \"bioO (~40 bp palindrome), bound cooperatively by two holo-BirA monomers\", \"role\": \"corepressor-activated transcriptional repressor of the biotin biosynthesis (bio) operon\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "high",
      "cat:crossChecked": true,
      "cat:lastChecked": {
        "@type": "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date",
        "@value": "2026-06-22"
      },
      "cat:sourceQuote": "Eisenstein & Beckett (1999): the adenylate-bound protein assembles into dimers with an equilibrium constant of 11 microM; site-specific DNA binding and protein dimerization are obligatorily linked in the system. Abbott & Beckett (1993): the BirA-biotin operator (bioO) complex consists of two holo-repressor monomers per operator site; the operator is a 40 base pair imperfect inverted palindrome.",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:usefulness": "high",
      "cat:usefulnessRationale": "Directly specifies the control logic (repressible regulation), the corepressor molecule (bio-5'-AMP) at physiologically relevant concentrations, the target operator (bioO with precise 40 bp size and binding stoichiometry), and the molecular prerequisite (homodimerization). This is essential operational knowledge for designers selecting or deploying BirA as a regulated transcriptional repressor.",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:10529178"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:10529178"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:birA_claim_regulation_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "Holo-BirA (with bound bio-5'-AMP) homodimerizes and binds the 40-bp bioO operator palindrome as a corepressor, repressing the biotin biosynthesis operon; bio-5'-AMP availability sets repressor activity."
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:birA_claim_regulation_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "secondary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:birA_claim_sequence_variant",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "verified",
      "cat:claimType": "sequence_variant",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"effect\": \"promiscuous proximity-dependent biotinylation; ~100-fold reduced bio-5'-AMP affinity; defective self-association and DNA binding\", \"labeling_radius_nm\": \"~20-30\", \"mutation\": \"R118G\", \"name\": \"BirA* (BioID)\", \"position_verified\": \"residue 118 is R in this sequence (1-based)\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "high",
      "cat:crossChecked": true,
      "cat:lastChecked": {
        "@type": "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date",
        "@value": "2026-06-22"
      },
      "cat:sourceQuote": "One such BirA mutant (R118G, hereafter called BirA*), which is defective in both self-association and DNA binding, displays an affinity for bioAMP two orders of magnitude less than that of the wild-type enzyme... roughly 50% of detected proteins likely reside within \u223c20\u201330 nm of the nearest LaA molecule.",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Introduction / Discussion",
      "cat:usefulness": "high",
      "cat:usefulnessRationale": "Selection-relevant variant with operationally actionable parameters: specifies the ~20-30 nm proximity-labeling radius (critical design specification), quantifies bio-5'-AMP affinity loss (100-fold), and explains functional consequence (promiscuous neighbor biotinylation) that directly guides experimental use of BioID.",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:22412018"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:22412018"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:birA_claim_sequence_variant_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "The R118G mutant (BirA*, used in BioID) is defective in self-association and DNA binding and binds bio-5'-AMP ~100-fold more weakly than wild type, so it prematurely releases reactive bio-5'-AMP and biotinylates neighbouring proteins promiscuously within ~20-30 nm."
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:birA_claim_sequence_variant_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:birA_claim_sequence_variant_turboid",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "sources-pending",
      "cat:claimType": "sequence_variant",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"TurboID\": {\"mutations_vs_WT\": 15, \"size_kDa\": 35}, \"engineering\": \"yeast display-based directed evolution\", \"labeling_time\": \"~10 minutes\", \"miniTurbo\": {\"mutations_vs_WT\": 13, \"n_terminal_deletion\": \"aa 1-63\", \"size_kDa\": 28}}",
      "cat:confidence": "medium",
      "cat:crossChecked": false,
      "cat:lastChecked": {
        "@type": "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date",
        "@value": "2026-06-22"
      },
      "cat:sourceQuote": "Our engineering efforts yielded two promiscuous ligases: 35 kD TurboID, with 15 mutations relative to wild-type BirA; and 28 kD miniTurbo, with N-terminal domain deleted and 13 mutations relative to wild-type BirA... enable 10-minute PL in cells with non-toxic and easily deliverable biotin.",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Abstract / Results",
      "cat:usefulness": "high",
      "cat:usefulnessRationale": "Provides specific, quantitative parameters (size, mutation count, deletion range, labeling time) that directly inform design choices and help users select between TurboID/miniTurbo variants for experimental applications",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:30125270"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:30125270"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:birA_claim_sequence_variant_turboid_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:comment": "Could not access full primary text to verify exact mutation counts; Addgene plasmid databases (derivative sources of the original work) consistently list 14 TurboID mutations and 12 miniTurbo mutations, not 15 and 13 as claimed.",
      "rdfs:label": "TurboID (35 kDa, 15 mutations vs wild-type BirA) and miniTurbo (28 kDa, N-terminal domain aa 1-63 deleted plus 13 mutations) are directed-evolution variants that catalyse proximity labeling far faster than BioID, enabling 10-minute biotin labeling in cells and organisms."
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:birA_claim_sequence_variant_turboid_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:birA_claim_structure",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "verified",
      "cat:claimType": "structure",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"c_terminal\": \"six-stranded antiparallel beta-sheet sandwich\", \"central\": \"seven-stranded mixed beta-sheet, alpha-helices on one face, solvent-exposed face carries the active site\", \"n_terminal\": \"alpha-helical helix-turn-helix DNA-binding domain\", \"pdb\": \"1BIB\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "high",
      "cat:crossChecked": true,
      "cat:lastChecked": {
        "@type": "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date",
        "@value": "2026-06-22"
      },
      "cat:sourceQuote": "The structure of BirA is highly asymmetric and consists of three domains. The N-terminal domain is mostly alpha-helical, contains a helix-turn-helix DNA-binding motif... The central domain consists of a seven-stranded mixed beta-sheet with alpha-helices covering one face. The other side of the sheet is largely solvent-exposed and contains the active site. The C-terminal domain comprises a six-stranded, antiparallel beta-sheet sandwich.",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Abstract",
      "cat:usefulness": "medium",
      "cat:usefulnessRationale": "Describes operationally relevant domain architecture (DNA-binding vs catalytic domains) useful for understanding BirA variants like BioID/TurboID, but somewhat redundant with the feature note in the part description.",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:1409631"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:1409631"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:birA_claim_structure_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "BirA is a three-domain protein: an N-terminal alpha-helical helix-turn-helix DNA-binding domain, a central seven-stranded mixed beta-sheet catalytic/active-site domain, and a C-terminal antiparallel beta-sheet domain."
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:birA_claim_structure_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-engine",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
