    {
      "@id": "part:lambda_attP_claim_host_range",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "pending",
      "cat:claimType": "host_range",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"host\": \"Escherichia coli and related bacteria\", \"integration\": \"single-copy at chromosomal lambda attB\", \"requires\": \"lambda Int (IHF host-supplied; Xis for excision)\", \"stability\": \"stable without antibiotic selection after integration\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "high",
      "cat:crossChecked": false,
      "cat:sourceQuote": "They can be integrated in single copies into the chromosomes of Escherichia coli and related bacteria ... CRIM plasmids are integrated into the chromosome by site-specific recombination at one of five different phage attachment sites ... Following integration, integrants are stably maintained in the absence of antibiotic selection.",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Abstract",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:11591683"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:11591683"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:lambda_attP_claim_host_range_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "Functions as a single-copy chromosomal integration site in Escherichia coli and related bacteria when supplied with lambda Int: a CRIM plasmid carrying this attP integrates at the chromosomal lambda attB by site-specific recombination and is stably maintained without selection; Xis-mediated excision is reversible."
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:lambda_attP_claim_host_range_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-workflow",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:lambda_attP_claim_mechanism",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "pending",
      "cat:claimType": "mechanism",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"accessory_factors\": [\"IHF\", \"Xis (excision/directionality)\", \"Fis (excision)\"], \"binding_sites\": 16, \"cognate_protein\": \"lambda Int\", \"cognate_site\": \"lambda_attB\", \"common_core\": \"15 bp (overlap TTTATAC)\", \"functional_length_bp\": 240, \"recombinase_family\": \"tyrosine recombinase (lambda Int family)\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "high",
      "cat:crossChecked": false,
      "cat:sourceQuote": "Int carries out a reaction that is highly directional, tightly regulated, and depends upon an ensemble of accessory DNA bending proteins acting on 240 bp of DNA encoding 16 protein binding sites.",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Abstract",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:26104711"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:26104711"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:lambda_attP_claim_mechanism_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "Recombination substrate for bacteriophage lambda integrase (Int), a tyrosine recombinase. Int plus the host bending protein IHF assemble an intasome on attP that recombines with attB; the ~240 bp attP encodes 16 protein-binding sites (arm-type and core-type Int sites, three IHF sites, Xis and Fis sites) that drive a highly directional, tightly regulated integration reaction via a Holliday-junction intermediate."
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:lambda_attP_claim_mechanism_ihf_bend",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "pending",
      "cat:claimType": "mechanism",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"bend_angle_deg\": \">160\", \"ihf_sites\": [\"H'\", \"H1\", \"H2\"], \"readout\": \"indirect (minor groove / A-tract)\", \"structure\": \"PDB 1IHF (IHF + 35 bp lambda H' DNA)\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "medium",
      "cat:crossChecked": false,
      "cat:sourceQuote": "Here, we report the crystal structure of IHF complexed with 35 bp of DNA. The DNA is wrapped around the protein and bent by >160 degrees ... IHF contacts the DNA exclusively via the phosphodiester backbone and the minor groove and relies heavily on indirect readout to recognize its binding sequence.",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Abstract",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:8980235"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:8980235"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:lambda_attP_claim_mechanism_ihf_bend_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "The three IHF sites (H', H1, H2) impose sharp protein-induced DNA bends that condense attP into the recombinogenic intasome. IHF bound at H' bends DNA by >160 degrees (a DNA U-turn), contacting only the minor groove and phosphate backbone and relying on indirect readout of an A-tract."
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:lambda_attP_claim_mechanism_ihf_bend_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-workflow",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:lambda_attP_claim_mechanism_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-workflow",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:lambda_attP_claim_sequence_feature",
      "@type": "cat:FunctionalClaim",
      "cat:analysisStatus": "pending",
      "cat:claimType": "sequence_feature",
      "cat:claimValue": "{\"clone_length_bp\": 387, \"left_boundary_from_core_center_bp\": \"between 106 and 152\", \"minimal_attP_bp\": 250, \"right_boundary_from_core_center_bp\": \"between 68 and 99\"}",
      "cat:confidence": "high",
      "cat:crossChecked": false,
      "cat:sourceQuote": "In order to recombine with the bacterial attachment site (attB), the phage attachment site must retain about 250 base pairs of its original sequence. On the left side, the essential sequence extends beyond 106 base pairs from the center of the 15-base-pair common core sequence but not beyond 152 base pairs. On the right side the required sequence extends beyond 68 base pairs but not beyond 99 base pairs from the center of the core.",
      "cat:sourceQuoteFrom": "primary",
      "cat:sourceSection": "Abstract",
      "dcterms:references": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:6251450"
      },
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": {
        "@id": "https://identifiers.org/pubmed:6251450"
      },
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": {
        "@id": "part:lambda_attP_claim_sequence_feature_provenance"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "Functional attP requires about 250 bp of phage sequence around the common core; deletion mapping bounds the essential sequence to beyond 106 (not beyond 152) bp left of the core center and beyond 68 (not beyond 99) bp to the right. This 387 bp clone therefore comfortably contains the minimal functional attP."
    },
    {
      "@id": "part:lambda_attP_claim_sequence_feature_provenance",
      "@type": "prov:Activity",
      "cat:agent": "annotate-part-workflow",
      "cat:fromDoc": "primary",
      "cat:method": "ai-extraction"
    },
